```text
void Prim() {
    // Initialize:
    V(T) = { r }; E(T) = ∅;
    d[r] = 0; near[r] = r;
    for v ∈ V \ V(T) {
        d[v] = c[r,v]; near[v] = r;
    }

    // Iteration:
    for (k=2; k<=n,k++) {
        Find v ∈ V \ V(T) satisfying: d[v] = min { d[i] : i ∈ V \ V(T) };
        V(T) = V(T) ∪ { v }; E(T) = E(T) ∪ { (v, near[v]) };
        for v' ∈ V \ V(T)
            if (d[v'] > c[v,v']) {
                d[v'] = c[v,v']; near[v'] = v;
            }
    }
}
```

- Prepare data for finding “safe” edge process
- $d[v]$: the edge with minimum weight connecting vertex $v$ *(not yet in the spanning tree $T$)* to other vertex of $T$
- $T$ is the minimum spanning tree;
- Computation time: $O(|V|^2)$

[Diagram: Prim’s algorithm grows a spanning tree one vertex at a time by repeatedly choosing the cheapest edge that connects the current tree to a new vertex. The labels $d[v]$ and $near[v]$ keep track of the best known connection for each outside vertex, which makes the next “safe” edge easy to identify and update.]

```text
void Prim(G, C) //G: graph; C: weight matrix
{
    Select an arbitrary vertex r ∈ V;
    Initialize: tree T=(V(T), E(T)) where V(T) = {r} and E(T)=∅;
    while (T has < n vertices)
    {
        Among edges connecting a vertex of T to other vertex not in T: find the edge with minimum weight
        (u, v) is the minimum weight where u ∈ V(T) and v ∈ V(G) − V(T)
        E(T) ← E(T) ∪ { (u, v) };
        V(T) ← V(T) ∪ { v }
        add vertex v and edge (u,v) to tree T
    }
}
```

[Diagram: The slide explains Prim’s greedy process for building a minimum spanning tree by growing a connected tree from one starting vertex. At each step, it chooses the cheapest edge that expands the tree without creating a cycle, which is what guarantees the final tree is minimum-cost.]
